The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider who forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting for much longer.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers are working on the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the ČTů telecommunications authority, which drew attention to the fact that the price of a text is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's last steps in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - for some customers of Czech mobile phone operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a battle announcement.
It may sound paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are happy to see that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably find hardly any more frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual suppliers into the mobile market resulted in a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators had to respond.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market in the UK, there were similar votes as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February of this year we reported on the launch of the virtual provider of mobile services in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country's fifth largest supplier.
The financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U: fon, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profit as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobile commerce in Poland shows, it can also be a rather good move to focus on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose mobile - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be found in the Czech Republic.
The press spokesman of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services. "
In the Czech Republic, mobile phone operators mean
But it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
It will be more of a market entry of mobile services in other countries in our region, "says in a phone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press officer of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For a long time now, the GTS Nowa group has shown its interest in starting a virtual mobile service provider, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of company customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them, "said the press officer of the group Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifications in relation to other markets.
No subject has yet addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area, "says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specific features of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in a rare way to the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to continue to build."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term. "
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we consider to be the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet. "
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, and another would be more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus to a fall in profits.
So why should one make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can draw on a line when it comes to something also shows the long back and forth about the creation of U: fon.
The most likely pressure in the direction of ČTů was the company T-Mobile at the time when U: fon was on the market.
This is also confirmed by the publicly available information from the ČTů web pages.
But now U: fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: "The bankruptcy of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would put high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services. "
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not only the ČTů's attitude, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries, does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
The Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS) is the sole body of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition.
This, however, referred to this whole problem in its very typical way.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile service provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers, "said in his reply to our question Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by the representatives of the providers.
This is more than a matter of concern to an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a country where virtual providers work in a normal way, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services."
It is likely, however, that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking that the three mobile operators are almost already in line, which is the result of their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of any action against competition in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its action on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications, "said Chalupa in its statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTů, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators will have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if this argument is not followed, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are very similar.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Nowa) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The shift of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS dissociates itself from the whole matter.
This was already observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment of the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of the ČTū's powers to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must only know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right if no one looks
The functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are more than one in the Czech mobile networks, is not taken into account.
They are companies which issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partly public.
They are usually companies operating in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, own mobile telephone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company is a classic company customer with the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the relevant society," replied Martina Kemrová to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not talk about the responsibility of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not give them negligible profits, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all these companies' services are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone in their name, so they cannot fully have it like the normal customers of mobile phone operators. "
But this alone would have to be at least strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile operators keep an eye on such a procedure, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they do not know and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the entry of virtual suppliers has led to a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In virtually all countries, where virtual providers have been created, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their creation from being virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was at these very moments that the regulatory bodies, which by no means tried to protect the interests of mobile operators but of their customers, were involved.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved the first virtual operator, and this followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that inclarity in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we do not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem where is my country on the occasion of the day of the Czech state in a ceremony.
The hymn was re-recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The song was written by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The workers of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can now listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
In the past, he had told the Czech radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo variants, which are striking and popular.
"From the very beginning I tried to keep a clear diction with both and then with the choir, so that you can understand the text well, so that a harmony can be established," the conductor said.
The Czech national anthem will take its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first recorded in 1834 on the stage of the "Städdetheater" in the original Czech play "Fidlovačka" by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was made by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people took it spontaneously.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven state symbols remained after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
