On Wednesday, the Prague transport companies will also transport to a chip for the first time.
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of the Prague transport companies as a date on which the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus, who will carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Chipcard Opencard.
The passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and be able to play it on their chipcard at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylasy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons have also been available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait for their paper tickets regularly in long queues.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is recorded on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"In these places, a switch with trained staff is also available to the travellers, who will advise interested parties on the Internet purchase and will also record the coupon on the map," said the spokesman of the Martin Opattný project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the Opencard, which are installed in some U-Bahn vestibules.
What do those machines look like?
They are red, remember a ticket, the passengers may have noticed them in the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"At present there are five of them in the city, but it is supposed to be eighty by the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
You just have to insert the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon is playing itself.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban slopes and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia get to the capital.
"In the trains that are part of the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading equipment to check the validity of the coupons after time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization. This organisation is the one to set up the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's checkout.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked position at the side of the checkout.
