In order to close this gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends a bilingual transition period in education for those who first learn English.
However, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, is contrary to his interest in reducing the distance in school services.
Let's take the example of "Sixth Street Prep," a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
However, in 2008, an amazing 100% fourth-class student passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth school year were rated as well in the English examination.
This amazing success was achieved with other methods than those that are preferred by Obama.
The sixth street school focuses on review and exercise, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is taking the approach to training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama is supposed to take into account, says the school leader Linda Mikes.
