Isabel Bayón recovers the memory of the dancer from Sevilla Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville adores a dancer who also came from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in Triana and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first women to fight for the emancipation of the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf, and Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, a vegetarian, and sat down for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her mark in the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the period between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which I thought was impossible."
'We are not trying to tell about her life, but to keep her Esprit, 'said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The dance of the butterfly ', for example, seemed like Guajira, or' the dance of the snake ', like tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area, 'she says.
The production expects two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel on one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with Flamenco-master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
"Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work and I am very honored. '
The production also includes musical composition and the gitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes on the role of the companion of the artists who were in love with Divas.'
This work also tells in a certain way about this woman's life, which became known in places as far as India, the United States or Russia, and also in the whole of Europe, even though she has normally lived in London.
"I wanted to recall her, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a certain epoch and whose works no one now knows and therefore even less appreciate her," says Bayón.
The performance will take place today at 20: 30 at the Theater Lope de Vega.
