Conversation - The blood that got safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most secure and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has recovered public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of the contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI and hepatitis C virus.
In the light of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public investigation carried out by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of bringing light to the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and of drawing up guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to give his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the management of blood canned in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, almost 38% of the people had confidence in the blood-reserve system in Quebec, Dr. Décary remembers.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canned products and by working in this area over the following years, we have recovered public confidence, 'she says, before she proudly stresses that in the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Decary is aware that 'trust is something very fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At this time, we witnessed many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation of 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we are looking at one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease is only slowly progressing, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was being transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technology for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the NST tests, which allow the virus to be detected directly in the donor's blood, rather than the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is in danger of receiving HIV-infected blood.
'In other words, you have to distribute 12 million blood cells before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cones each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted through a blood conserve.
I believe that you can feel comfortable these days when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe to restore health, 'says the director of Hema-Quebec.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can get into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, just like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We have to keep monitoring ', Dr. Décary continues before she stresses that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Quebec also has to provide a sufficient supply.
The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer treatment is more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood supply network, which, on average, only 3% of the population suitable for the blood donation of Quabec. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older who meets the selection criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from the blood donation for a year.
'With these 3% we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
The lack of supplies is very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network when they become older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give blood, but above all to hold them and to make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that it is rare to find the time to spend an hour donating blood, 'regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood canned, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in serious fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical blood bank in Quebecs.
In the umbilical cord, previously considered to be a biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousands of umbilical blood samples, and we plan to lose more than a thousand per year.
"We should probably start to make it available for transplants at the beginning of next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical blood loss as very popular.
"Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to it ', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals of Quabec.
