Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In her edition of September 17, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director-General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
The latter confirms and follows an orwellian logic that the world's largest gold winning company sought a slander claim for six million against three authors and a small medium-less publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of slander claims, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely ignored by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold is the best way to hold a public debate, to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial ends, the authors and the editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual regime that makes the other side mundane and also detracts anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things in front of public opinion.
In contrast to what is going on in many of the countries in which Barrick is working gold, debates in Canada are usually held through the exchange of ideas and not by the bailiff.
It would therefore have been enough for the gold mine to have published its books and files and opened a real debate through the newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams that could have brought light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate, while at the same time disrespecting the opinions of the public at the same time?
