The Psychology of Overdoing - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus to overrate the price offered.
Neurologers and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of striatum, a complex below the brain bark, was measured at the loss of the auction, in which the opponent's overbid played a significant role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by the avoidance of overaction of the striate.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have made additional research into the follow-up of the money.
In this case, three groups should be involved against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars in reward in case they were the winners of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that the emphasis was on winning, while the emphasis was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were prepared to take higher action than those in the control or "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have, in fact, only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding the risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation available "- said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, for example, through the digestive tract (through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
In any case, travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Then the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the much more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected patients is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most of the infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen is deeply destroying the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular monitoring, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
The number of chronic hepatitis C patients in the world is currently estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, which will prevent the risk of infection and prevent the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As the latest research shows, religious faith is a kind of "painkiller" that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: the extent to which faith in God influences the human feeling of pain, the British paper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain-scan technology, it was even possible to prove that Catholics could activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, also philosophers and theologians from different departments of the university participate.
In the experiment, a radiant device was connected to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance, as they chose Vincent's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and was felt to be reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while looking at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "in safety" at the sight of the Mother of God as if they were "worried," and that they felt "peace and quiet."
During the view of the religious painting, they reported more than 12% less pain than when they had seen Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the attempt, said that one could also cause similar effects with other, strong-acting images also with the atheists, one only had to find the appropriate photo.
"We would have to find a picture that is very positive, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and does so in many cases," says Wright.
According to these excellent results, the only question remains what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another similar painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
