Schmidt said that after ten years of world-changing work, Google was still only at the beginning of the information collection.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wanted Google to be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job really fits me?" but software programs are not yet able to do so, as they do not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the search terms would be registered in the course of their Internet search, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save his own search course and later to use it so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the same logic is also based on the so-called "recommendations," with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on the previous preferences.
However, users are wondering what happens in the event of data abuse - "When you look at what I do" - some people are worried about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the potential power represented by the company, which acts as a source of fear, and less the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or the desire for power against the power that many Internet users have to reject.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of a start, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
One example of this was the recent action against paedophilia in Brazil, in the course of which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut," which also enabled the identification of paedophilia.
However, users who were concerned about personal rights could still breathe up in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organisation EFF, successfully moved to court against the FBI: therefore, Google cannot be forced to issue information to the FBI on a secret request in the future with any point of the Constitution.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the issue of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms by reference to the Youth Protection Act adopted years ago, but it has been denied the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, retroactively to two months.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who do not like to issue their personal data because by using Google services they fear the loss of their private and intimate sphere, scourge the company with the indignation that is due to the conservative companies.
However, the American "Geek culture," which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, is the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, as opposed to Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google does not require its users to have any identification codes, unlike Microsoft, and provides its services free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seem to be far more attractive, youthful and cooler than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the Geeks look through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has been in the focus especially in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0."
In fact, the "Web 2.0" is about nothing but collaboration, in other words, the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individual, the main thing remains the same, that is to show themselves publicly.
An average young person can manage his profile at the same time on several community portals - from Facebook via Xanga, it can connect them with each other through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and it can finally include all this in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically represent the latest photo galleries that are flocked on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other examples prove that when looking at the party photos of the last night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee is being released because he is only too honest in his blog with his anger about the company's management - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
The one who leads an online life is what it reveals - in this way one could formulate the basic idea behind the behaviour of today's youth.
And those who try to keep something secret, or even to circumvent the Google monopoly, can do so - such as Scroogle, a tool that, while accessing Google's search engine, deliberately leaves no trace.
Not a few people deliberately register on community sites so they can't be found, but also Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphic tools and RSS feeds, can be used with alternative versions that are not linked to a huge server park and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
However, public opinion is waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), the advertising space of AdWords / AdSense is threatening the revenues of the advertising agencies, and the more and more quickly introduced services are not only causing the head break, but also other software developers.
However, critical viewers also find the disconcerting counterpoles: for example, the Group's management has completely rejected a protest from the employees after the fees of the company's own kindergarten have been doubled, and the management said that the multiple food of the employees is too expensive, but all of this is very mild against the fact that in 2006 Google even went on its knees before the Chinese government and agreed to an agreement that all the regime-critical hits, or those that are in breach of the good taste, would be filtered out.
The Group's internal regulation is that in advance it is not a new service, but only if it is already available. However, the events of the coming months and years could be a lot of a change: while some of them think that Google's book and magazine and archiving project is now taking on a scale that the company would have to deal with the Supreme Court soon, others are rather concerned about the "health" system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the substance - for example, "Scroogled," the famous novel by Cory Doctorov, describes in the best Orwellian manner a future in which a human being becomes frighteningly close thanks to Google-related data.
