Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which the Nissan engineers of Hummel were inspired in the creation of new accident of avoiding systems.
In cooperation with the Tokioter University, Nissan has built the BR23C-controlled biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "shield," Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can be seen in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled spacer.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to the board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in second parts, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tyres around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctively taking place.
"If it were not, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they evade other bees.
And this has to be done in a fraction of a second.
However, as opposed to the bees, the evasive can not go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the wendability of the tyres.
While the bees are here infinitely open to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotation, or the acceleration and braking of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh said it depends on the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to save it.
This device must only process and react to some inputs per second.
It does not have to save it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous manoeuvres, so that it is constantly using only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be in production in the next ten years as standard.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the target.
