Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today in Paris, the European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which is held this year by the EU President-in-Office of the Council of the European Union, France, has begun.
In her speech to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, Fidesz Member of the European People's Party, drew attention in particular to the education sector, as it is one of the most serious legal violations that Roma children face, and this is the main obstacle to their application.
The high-level conference was opened by the French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The participants included representatives of governments, the European social partners and the most important European legal and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
As reported by the Fidesz press office, Járóka has pointed out that, in addition to discrimination in the job search, the Roma would be displaced from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma young people do not have middle-school education and, thanks to poor primary education, only a small part of them can get a higher education degree."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education was a fundamental human right, which would have a key role to play in the application of other human rights.
Investment in early education for Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU Member States.
In the opinion of the Members, it is important that these links become as broad a circle as possible - that is, the Roma and the non-Roma.
The sooner a Roma student starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market are increasing, and through income and turnover tax they contribute to national expenditure.
"As citizens of the Union, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - the poor and segregated education must be stopped" - said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member has said, a common, objective and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of disintegration in the education sector, and it is essential to ensure that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly complied with.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunity to contribute to the future of Europe as a full citizen," Járóka called for.
Since the Berlin Congress last year, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advance of the objectives of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities."
