Despite the election debacle, there are no heads at the time; at the head of the Bavarian CSU, the staff debates were postponed.
Head of the party Erwin Huber and Prime Minister Beckstein remain in their offices, the question is only how long this grace lasts.
The fate of the tandem after the catastrophic 17% loss of voice will be decided on the last weekend of October at the extraordinary party day.
The much-cut duo, however, already made it clear that it does not want to stick on its armchairs.
In doing so, they want to appease the angry group and the party base, which demanded personal consequences one day after the "Bavarian tsunami" in view of the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years ago - admittedly, under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber, who was at his career center - the Christian-Social Union still reached 60.7 percent. But now, one year after the coup against Stoiber, they were able to secure only 43.4 percent of the votes.
For 46 years, the CSU was a "single government" in Bavaria, which generates 18 percent of German GDP.
The Conservatives remain the decisive force in the southern federal state, which is also important for the Hungarian economy, but will have to rule in a coalition in the future.
As the first sign of the party-internal restructuring, the potential successor of Huber, Vice-President and Federal Minister of Agriculture Horst Seehofer is also involved in the investigation team, which is conducting exploratory talks with the liberal FDP, or the right-wing "Free Voter" on a possible Munich coalition.
The irony of fate is that with the list of "Free Voters" the Gabriele Pauli comes into the legislature, whose anti-stoiber appearance first took advantage of the Huber-Beckstein Duo, in order to then serve the target-seeking politician mercilessly.
The CSU leadership now focuses all its forces on the stabilisation of Beckstein.
In this transition process, Stoiber, who has so far pulled the strings out of the background, will have an active role to play. The former Prime Minister and CSU Chairman called the 28 September "the most bitter day of his political career."
On Monday, Huber made a few toxic comments towards CDU - in his view, the CSU would have earned far more support from the sister party.
Other CSU politicians interpreted the defeat as a signal to the CDU and thus to Angela Merkel.
If the CSU, which has also contributed a great deal to the success of 2005 at national level, is not to be put back on its feet with a common force, Merkel cannot become a Chancellor again after the Bundestag elections in September 2009.
Merkel, who has made no sense of her disappointment at the Fiasko, believes that the CSU's land loss will not have a negative impact on the great coalition in Berlin.
What is relative, however, is that the wounded CSU will not be easier to rule, and the crisis of the Social Democrats will continue.
With 18.6 percent, the SPD has achieved its best result in Bavaria since 1946.
