Mp3 player under charge: risk of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a report published today in Brussels cites the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on the EU's current and recently identified health risks).
"The report, as it says in a note, makes it clear that 5-10% of those who hear loud music with portable music devices for at least five years a week risk the permanent loss of their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people who usually place portable music equipment and mobile phones on a high volume will damage their hearing without knowing it inextricably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"There is a clear risk from the scientific findings, as the European Union says, which is pressing for rapid action.
What really matters is to raise the awareness of consumers and make this information a common good.
In the light of this scientific knowledge, we must re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology. "
Brussels had entrusted the independent scientific committee with the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists - as the EU Communication concludes - confirm that we are quite concerned and that the European Commission, together with the other members of the European Union and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise that comes from portable music and similar equipment."
There is already a European standard at the moment, which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from too much noise.
One can very much limit these damage, in which one can reach solutions such as the reduction of volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the European Scientific Committee points out that, if the users of portable music equipment are only five hours a week (louder than 89 decibels) listen to music so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum sound level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this line of music risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would mean 5-10% of the users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated to be between 2.5 and 10 million people in the European Union.
