The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already revealed itself a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's 700 billion-dollar savings package: a large part of the Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's edition of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis in the run-up to the Republican Party, which is becoming more and more divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favoured the state institutions and the business community and the neo-conservative, who is hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and, inter alia, wins voters in the south and the centre of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example, which has just been mentioned, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing, or even already is,: not only in the US, even in the whole of the West and perhaps beyond, will be affected by it.
In both countries and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-awaited events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unheard renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline of the banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage a huge amount of the assets of households living in a single state.
This is a direct political problem for governments: how to behave with the families concerned, which is also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears to be global in economic terms, but politically it is almost purely national.
In this way, political internationalism seems to have lost its right to speak, and it is clear that the EU has provided evidence of this, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, is not able to find a common way.
Therefore, all now expect the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, among other things, the distribution of aid funds: since the crisis has become more and more serious, only the US has been in a position to save itself without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: therefore, two not to be overestimated conditions - under certain circumstances - to which otherwise no international organisation or market will be able to use them in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, perfectly in line with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated with a most closely related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is just now that we have been so convinced that we have long been in a united kingdom, in a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other in the world, but are still very much connected with a narrow-cut piece of earth - a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favour of another, who lives in a harvest-less, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short entry.
Who territory, who government, who says politics, thus also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for reputable lead ships, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaders, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more worrying aspect: a loss of confidence, an impatience, a picture of inexpedience, a sense of distance, all of which is directed at a whole class of managers in the Western countries.
It seems that the belief among large parts of the population is the way to go, that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is the majority as more and more foreign and superior.
The demand for leadership therefore feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of disarming the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in the unanticipated "revolts" of the voters and in the unmediated change of the collective state of mind of the past: beginning with the rise of the Conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in the UK, towards the rebellion of the American deputies against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, its parties, its programmes, but also its rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say its format, more and more problems of understanding, and therefore less representative of what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West and is being further strengthened and driven by the financial crisis to overdimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply excessive to speak of a "rebellion of the masses."
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The superglue that goes up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to a glue and to be able to climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached the target.
With a glue applied on a surface of only 2.5 square cm, the researchers have succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO - an American magazine has published the results of the researchers of the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material created by the research team is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be seen as a set of spaghetti-ordered tubes," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the gecko, which are covered by microscopic harnesses that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and grinding paper have shown that the new glue is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the reptiles' feet and at the same time "without any problems from the wall," said Lising Dai, researcher of the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Lising Dai.
For example, to go up on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but the researchers think more of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also heads of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in the space sector.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER NATURE OF RESEARCH - also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the California scientists present a microfibre adhesive that, like hair, cleanse itself from the dust by moving on a surface and thus always maintain a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in the summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin abundance, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the body's absorption.
David Bailey, Professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly pointed out the risk of packed as well as fresh fruit juices in connection with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again made an alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to the extent that they are practically eliminated and thus the health of the patients is at risk.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular medicines, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDIKAMENTE IN GEFAHR - The same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the risks of this mixture and stressed to pay attention to what is being drunk in combination with drugs such as diazepan or metadone.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, the appeal by Michele Carruba, the director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually passed on immediately to the various international producers who are so free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is appropriate to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there are any doubts, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or a doctor, "says the Ansa Agency's expert.
