Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package will be released
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft's office, is gaining an ever-increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both under freelance and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself with some new features to the audience: in addition to a revised and now Spartan-designed initial menu, a compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x is finally achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, there was an interest in the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Some new features are also interesting, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which, for example, facilitates sending via email. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics processing modules and at the same time to keep the original appearance of the page.
This way, you can now also generate "hybrid" PDF files that extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format with the elements of a table and a text processing system.
Cooperation is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed several times by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the text processing system, a frame is assigned to each processor in order to guarantee a better correction process.
