Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historical cinema
The historical cinemas close due to the beneficiary multiplex cinema.
"A city without cinema channels is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the great urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multiroom complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only appears to be invincible and irrevocable, but also bears the features of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom one has covered a piece of street full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a world of cinema that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the vast number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these collieries paid most of the cinemas in the large cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
One of the most affected regions is the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprit is the multiplex cinema, because it is these three regions in which the largest number of modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has been leading the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first is the preservation of the already existing one, because a hall in the city closes, not all of its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplexkino in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the lack of budget for the fund of the Trade Union: the government's debt burden is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros in the year would be necessary. "
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinema, has decided to protect it through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec, is the first such agreement in Italy to protect and support traditional cinema, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax concessions for the cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to go to the traffic limited areas of the centre and also to park at more favourable parking charges.
"It is a pleasant initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also develop new concepts.
But of course we also need a better audio and video equipment to be able to do something about the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Bagiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that made me start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso," even though I had played with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to not have to see the dust-covered posters.
