When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a non-sealed source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now does it seem to the world's major energy companies understand.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occult, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of generating energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and examined for 70 years; these studies have not happened to have significantly intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of sea energy was taken off, but now the environmental organisations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company that now relies on sea energy is Enersis, which in 2005 signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this message was published it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies in the traditional energy sector that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron is studying these technologies," says the spokesperson of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, and weighs the opportunity to work with us. "
It is about the acquisition of an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that is not to be underestimated, especially given that, especially in Alaska, oil is still being promoted by the US and President Bush has recently set in motion the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies are Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, who invest in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still under way, not least because the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce large-scale energy, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected bojets.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure in the swimmers via piston and cylinder.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval, and some of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, is already producing energy for a store and a parking lot using under-sea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorization to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Profit Research, a particular interest is now worth the potential that is in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, the solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
